ng who lives and who dies, we need to learn from COVID-19 quickly to prevent growing inequality and to reduce health inequalities in the future. COVID-19 is an unequal pandemic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aLynch, Julia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPickett, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Katherine E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831111967560 cprintz978144736123740uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447361251?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447361251zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447361251/original  a978-3-11-119675-6 Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA